<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

</TABLE>
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Several additional factors were considered in the cost analysis, including: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&bull;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Treatment of compliance costs for paragraphs that codify an existing EPA policy (i.e., elements that are presently
in effect but are not part of the existing regulation). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&bull;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Compliance with the existing and the proposed regulation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&bull;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Treatment of the effect of the proposed amendments on disposal capacity and disposal prices. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&bull;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Consideration of the time horizon for compliance costs, given the declining quantities of PCBs in use. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&bull;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Cost annualization methods. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=10 g=1 f=1 -->
Each topic is discussed below.  
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Treatment of costs for provisions that codify EPA policy.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In several instances, an EPA policy has been developed in response to new information received by EPA or concerns about
compliance problems, and the proposed rule would codify these policies. Because the existing regulations differ
from EPA's policies, two sets of cost estimates were prepared based on two different baselines. The strict language
of the existing regulations served as the first baseline, which was used to generate cost estimates for all sections
of the proposed regulations. Actual EPA policy or practice was used as the baseline for 29 provisions of the amendments.
In cases where the current EPA policy and the existing regulations do not differ, a single cost estimate was prepared
and applied in either case. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Compliance with the existing and the proposed regulations.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 All cost estimates were prepared assuming full compliance with the existing and the proposed regulations, although
in reality, many companies are not in full compliance with the existing regulations. This study is designed only to
estimate the costs of the proposed regulations; the actions necessary to achieve compliance with the existing regulations
are not considered. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Treatment of the effect of the proposed amendments on disposal capacity and disposal prices.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The analysis does not reflect possible effects of the proposed amendments on either disposal capacity or disposal
costs for PCB wastes. The proposed amendments include several elements that could reduce demand for disposal of PCB
wastes in chemical landfills, such as allowing for longer storage of some wastes and for use of alternative disposal
technologies. It is reasonable to anticipate that the availability of alternatives to TSCA permitted landfills
and incinerators will lower costs for disposal at those facilities. Nevertheless, these market changes were not
modeled in this study. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Consideration of future declines in the volume of PCB waste requiring disposal.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 In future years the amount of PCB waste will decline. Discussions with various industry representatives, however,
indicated that this waste stream still would be substantial for a number of years. Disposal of PCB-Contaminated soils
from remediation sites, one of the major categories of wastes addressed in the proposed regulations, is likely to
continue for several decades.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
1
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Given that the time horizon for waste disposal remains so long, a declining time horizon for compliance costs or cost
savings was not taken into account for this study. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<FOOTNOTE>
<FOOTNAME>
