<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) of this section does not meet the measurement-based objectives required in paragraph (a)(4)(i)(A)(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
1
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) or (a)(4)(i)(A)(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) of this section, then the treated material shall be disposed of based on its existing concentration in accordance
with the disposal requirements of paragraph (b) or paragraph (c) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
4
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
)(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) Bulk PCB remediation waste may be microencapsulated or vitrified on-site. Microencapsulated PCB remediation
waste must be homogenous to the point that it has no free liquid component as measured by Method 9095 (Paint Filter Liquids
Test) as described in SW&hyph;846 ``Test Methods for Evaluating Solid Wastes, Physical/Chemical Methods'' which
is available from NTIS. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
