<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
15. By adding 761.77 to subpart D to read as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
761.77
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
 Coordinated approval. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(a)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 General requirements.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Notwithstanding any other provision of this part, the EPA Regional Administrator for the Region in which a PCB disposal
or PCB commercial storage facility described in paragraphs (b) through (g) of this section is located may issue a TSCA
PCB Coordinated Approval to the persons described in those paragraphs if the conditions listed in this section are
met. A TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval will designate the persons who own and who are authorized to operate the facilities
described in paragraphs (b) through (g) of this section and will apply only to such persons. All requirements, conditions,
and limitations of any other permit or waste management document described in those paragraphs are deemed to be conditions
of the TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval whose violation is a prohibited act under section 15 of TSCA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Persons seeking a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval shall submit a request for approval by certified mail, return
receipt requested, to the Regional Administrator for the Region in which the activity will take place. Persons seeking
a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval for a new PCB activity shall submit the request for approval at the same time they seek
a permit, approval, or other action for a PCB waste management activity under any other Federal or State authority.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) The request for approval shall include a copy of the letter from EPA announcing or confirming the EPA ID Number issued
to the facility for conducting PCB activities; the name, organization, and telephone number of the individual who
is the point of contact for the non-TSCA Federal, State, or local permitting authority; a description of the waste
management activities to be conducted if a permit or other relevent waste management document has not been issued;
a copy of the relevant permit or waste management document specified in paragraphs (b) through (g) of this section;
and a certification that the person who owns or operates the facility is aware of and will adhere to the TSCA PCB reporting
and recordkeeping requirements at subparts J and K of this part. When a permit or other waste management document has
been issued for the PCB waste activity, a final copy of the non-TSCA document that will be used during the PCB activity,
including all requirements, conditions, and limitations, shall be submitted to the Regional Administrator. This
requirement may be waived, in writing, by the Regional Administrator. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) The Regional Administrator shall confirm receipt of the request for approval. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) The Regional Administrator shall review the request for approval for completeness, for compliance with the
requirements of paragraphs (b) through (g), and to ensure that the PCB activity for which approval is requested will
not present an unreasonable risk of injury to health or the environment. The Regional Administrator shall either:

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(A) Issue a written notice of deficiency explaining why the request for approval is deficient. In addition, the Regional
Administrator shall either: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
1
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) Request additional information, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) Deny the request for approval and require the person who owns or operates the PCB facility to submit an application
for a TSCA PCB approval; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(B) Issue a notice of TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval acknowledging the non-TSCA approval meets the regulatory requirements
under TSCA as written; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(C) Issue a notice of TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval that includes additional conditions that are necessary to implement
other sections of part 761 or that address the Regional Administrator's concerns associated with potential risks
of injury to health or the environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) If the Regional Administrator determines that conditions of the approval are not met, the Regional Administrator
may issue a notice of deficiency, revoke the TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval, or require the person to whom the TSCA PCB
Coordinated Approval was issued to submit an application for a TSCA PCB approval. Such a determination could be based
on, but would not necessarily limited to the following: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Compliance with paragraphs (b) through (g) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Operation of the approved process in a manner which may result in an unreasonable risk of injury to health or the
environment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Failure to comply with, expiration of, or revocation of the non-TSCA approval or of the program under which the
nonTSCA approval was issued. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) For CERCLA actions, completion of requirements conducted pursuant to a Record of Decision (ROD) or enforcement
decision document or failure of the owner or operator to comply with conditions of the ROD. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The Regional Administrator shall cease to recognize the non-TSCA approval as being the equivalent of a TSCA PCB
approval after a TSCA PCB approval has been issued for the facility. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Land disposal facilities.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The person who owns or operates a land disposal facility, that accepts PCB wastes and requires an approval under subpart
D of this part, shall have a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)(i) Has a permit issued by EPA or an authorized State Director under the Solid Waste Disposal Act as amended by the
Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments of 1984, section 3005(a) and 40 CFR parts 270 and 271, and is in compliance with
all permit conditions based on the requirements of 40 CFR part 264, subpart N; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program no less stringent than the TSCA
requirements found in this part; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the chemical waste landfill requirements at 761.75(b). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Incinerator
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. The person who owns and operates facilities used to incinerate PCB wastes may operate the facility under a TSCA PCB
Coordinated Approval if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)(i) Has a permit issued by EPA or an authorized State Director under the Solid Waste Disposal Act as amended by the
Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments of 1984, section 3005(a) and 40 CFR parts 270 and 271, and is in compliance with
the requirements at subpart O of 40 CFR 264.340 et seq.; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program no less stringent than the requirements
in this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the incineration requirements at 761.70(a)(1) through (9), (b)(1) and (2) and (c). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(d)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Research and development.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Persons conducting research and development (R&amp;D) into PCB disposal methods (regardless of PCB concentration),
may conduct R&amp;D under a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)(i) Has a permit issued by EPA or an authorized State Director under the Solid Waste Disposal Act as amended by the
Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments of 1984, section 3005(a) and 40 CFR parts 270 and 271, and is in compliance with
all permit conditions based on the requirements of 40 CFR parts 264 and 270.65, (or) 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program no less stringent than the requirements
in this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Alternate disposal technologies.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 Any person operating an alternative disposal method that provides PCB destruction equivalent to disposal in a 761.70
incinerator or a 761.60 high efficiency boiler and will not present an unreasonable risk of injury to health or the
environment may operate under a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program no less stringent than the requirements
in this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Commercial storage facility.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 The person who owns and operates commercial storage facilities used to store PCB wastes and is required to have an approval
under subpart D of this part, shall have a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)(i) Has a permit issued by the EPA or an authorized State Director under the Solid Waste Disposal Act as amended by
the Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments of 1984, section 3005(a) and 40 CFR parts 270 and 271, and is in compliance
with all permit conditions based on the requirements at 40 CFR part 264, subparts J, K and L, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program no less stringent than the requirements
in this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the storage requirements of 761.65(a), (c), (d)(2). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g)
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
 Site remediation
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. Any person conducting a cleanup of PCB remediation waste may conduct the cleanup under a TSCA PCB Coordinated Approval
if the person: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1)(i) Has a permit issued by EPA or an authorized State Director under the Solid Waste Disposal Act as amended by the
Hazardous and Solid Waste Amendments of 1984, section 3005(a) and 40 CFR parts 270 and 271, and is in compliance with
all permit conditions based on the requirements of 40 CFR part 264 et seq., 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Has a permit issued by a State Director pursuant to a State PCB disposal program, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iii) Is conducting a remedial action under CERCLA as amended, pursuant to a signed record of decision, consent order
or decree. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Complies with the conditions of that permit, record of decision, consent order or decree. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Complies with the reporting and recordkeeping requirements in subparts J and K of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 16. In 761.79 by adding an introductory paragraph, redesignating paragraphs (a) and (b) as (b) and (c), respectively,
adding new paragraphs (a), (d), (e), (f), (g), and (h) to read as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=80 g=1 f=1 -->
761.79
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=89 g=1 f=1 -->
Decontamination. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Solvents and other decontamination materials shall meet all use, safety, health, and disposal standards as required
by applicable Federal, State, and local laws and regulations. Compliance with the standards and procedures for decontamination
in this section does not provide relief or protection from any other applicable Federal, State, or local laws and regulations.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(a) The purpose of this section is to establish for this part, regulatory levels and self-implementing or standardized
decontamination levels and procedures for removing PCBs from equipment, structures, non-porous surfaces, liquids
or other materials to allow for reuse. Any person conducting a decontamination activity under this section becomes
a new generator of a PCB waste. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) For purposes of decontamination under this section, the solubility of PCBs in any solvent used must be 5 percent
or more by weight. The solvent may be reused for decontamination until it contains 50 ppm PCBs. All hydrocarbon solvent
used or reused for decontamination under this section that contains 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&lt;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
50 ppm PCB may be burned and marketed in accordance with the requirements for waste oil as promulgated in 761.20(e)
or decontaminated pursuant to this section. All chlorinated solvent at any concentration or other solvents 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
50 ppm PCB used for decontamination under this section shall be disposed of as a PCB in accordance with 761.60(a) or
decontaminated pursuant to this section. All other liquid or non-liquid PCBs resulting from decontamination under
this section and not otherwise regulated for disposal shall be disposed of in accordance with the provisions of 761.60(a)(1)
through (a)(3) or 761.61(a)(5)(i)(B), respectively, or decontaminated pursuant to this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) All equipment, structures, surfaces, liquids, or other materials decontaminated in accordance with the procedures
and standards of this section may be distributed in commerce or used in accordance with the provisions of 761.20(c)(5)
or (6). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) A written record must be established and maintained for a period of 3 years from the date of any decontamination
under this section. The record must show sampling locations and analytical results and must be retained at the site
of the decontamination or a copy of the record must be made available to EPA in a timely manner, if requested. This recordkeeping
requirement does not apply when sampling is not required under this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) For purposes of decontamination under this section, filtering, soaking, wiping, stripping of insulation, chopping,
scraping or the use of abrasives to remove or separate PCBs from contaminated surfaces or liquids does not require
a disposal approval under subpart D of this part. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Any person conducting decontamination activities under this section shall take measures to ensure that no solvent,
dust or particulate emissions containing PCBs are released to the environment from the decontamination area. Workers
shall wear or use protective clothing or equipment to protect against direct dermal contact or inhalation of PCBs
or materials containing PCBs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=37 g=1 f=1 -->
*&blank;&blank;*&blank;&blank;*&blank;&blank;*&blank;&blank;* 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(d) The decontamination standard for non-porous surfaces is less than or equal to 10 micrograms PCB/100 square centimeters
(
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
10 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=1 -->
m
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
g/100cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) as measured by a standard wipe test (761.123). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(e) Any non-porous surface in contact with free flowing mineral oil dielectric fluid (MODEF) at levels equal to or
less than 10,000 ppm PCBs (
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 10,000 ppm PCB) may be decontaminated as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Drain the free flowing MODEF and allow the residual surfaces to drain for an additional 15 hours. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Dispose of drained MODEF according to 761.60. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Submerge and soak the contaminated or potentially contaminated surfaces in sufficient clean (containing less
than 2 ppm PCBs (
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&lt;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
2 ppm PCBs)) kerosene such that there is a minimum of 800 milliliters (ml) of kerosene for each 100 square centimeters
(cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) of contaminated or potentially contaminated surface for at least 15 hours at room temperature (20
<!-- PJG 0017 degreeslatlong -->
&cir; C or greater). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Drain the kerosene from the surfaces. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Dispose of the drained kerosene in accordance with paragraph (a)(1) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) Confirmatory sampling is not required, but any person using this section to claim that a surface is decontaminated
must be able to substantiate that claim with records, photographs, video recordings, or other forms of documentation.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(f) Any non-porous surface in contact with free flowing MODEF containing greater than 10,000 ppm PCB (>10,000 ppm PCB)
in MODEF or askarel PCB (up to 70 percent PCB in a mixture of trichlorobenzenes and tetrachlorobenzenes) may be decontaminated
as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) Drain the free flowing MODEF or askarel and allow the residual surfaces to drain for an additional 15 hours. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Dispose of drained MODEF or askarel according to 761.60. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) Submerge and soak the contaminated or potentially contaminated surfaces in sufficient clean kerosene (containing

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&lt;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
2 ppm PCBs) such that there is a minimum of 800 ml of kerosene for each 100 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 of contaminated or potentially contaminated surface for at least 15 hours at room temperature (20
<!-- PJG 0017 degreeslatlong -->
&cir; C or greater). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Drain the kerosene from the surfaces. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) Dispose of the drained kerosene in accordance with paragraph (a)(1) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) Submerge and soak the surfaces previously submerged, soaked, and drained pursuant to paragraph (f)(3) of this
section in sufficient clean kerosene such that there is a minimum of 800 ml of kerosene for each 100 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
 of surface for at least 15 hours at 20
<!-- PJG 0017 degreeslatlong -->
&cir; C. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(7) Drain the kerosene from the surfaces. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(8) Dispose of the drained kerosene in accordance with paragraph (a) of this section. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(9) Confirmatory sampling is not required, but anyone using this section to claim that a surface is decontaminated
must be able to substantiate that claim. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(g) The decontamination standard for water containing PCBs is less than or equal to 0.5 micrograms per liter (i.e.,
approximately 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
0.5 parts per billion (ppb)) PCBs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(h) The decontamination standard for organic liquids containing PCBs, except for PCB remediation wastes, is less
than 2 milligrams per liter (i.e., approximately 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=6 f=2 -->
&lt;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
2 parts per million (ppm)) PCBs. 
