<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=2 -->
 APPENDIX I. _ Sample Site Selection, Sampling, and Analysis of Standard PCB Wipe Samples Taken for Purposes of Determining
a PCB Concentration for Abandonment and Disposal of Natural Gas Pipeline 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=2 -->
 1.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Applicability and Scope
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.1 These procedures apply to the selection of wipe sampling sites for natural gas pipe to be abandoned in place or disposed
of off-site according to 761.60(b)(5). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.2 Pipe or pipe segments always refers to natural gas pipe or segments of natural gas pipe. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.3 Wipe sampling shall only be done when there are no free flowing liquids present. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Definition of Standard Wipe Sample
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.1 A standard wipe test is defined in 761.123. A standard wipe sample is generated for chemical analysis using the
standard wipe test. The minimum surface area to be sampled shall be 100 square centimeters. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.2 Guidance for wipe sampling appears in the document entitled ``Wipe Sampling and Double Wash/Rinse Cleanup as
Recommended by the Environmental Protection Agency PCB Spill Cleanup Policy,'' available from the TSCA Assistance
Information Service, Enviromental Protection Agency, 401 M St., SW., Washington, DC 20460. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 3.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Sample Site Selection
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.1 There are three site selection parameters: position around the circumference of a selected pipe segment or pipe,
position along the length of a selected pipe segment or pipe, and selection of a pipe segment from a length of pipe or
population (group) of pipe segments. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.2 Position around the circumference of a pipe segment or pipe. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.2.1 When pipe or a pipe segment is accessed for sampling, the pipe shall be marked to identify the location of the bottom
of the pipe or pipe segment when the natural gas pipeline was in service. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.2.2 The inside center of the bottom of a pipe or pipe segment shall be sampled. The sample shall be centered on the bottom
of the pipe, that is, the sample shall encompass an equal area on both sides of the middle of the bottom of the pipe for
the entire length of the sample. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3 Position along the length of the pipe or pipe segment 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.1 The sample shall be taken 15 centimeters (6 inches) inside the end of a pipe or pipe segment at the bottom of the
pipe or pipe segment as determined in procedure 3.2 of this appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.2 If the sample site location selected in procedure 3.3.1 of this appendix is a porous surface (for example, there
is significant corrosion so as to shred the wipe material), then the sample site shall be moved inward (away from the
end of the pipe or pipe segment) until there is no such porous surface. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.3 There are three options in the event that there is no non-porous surface accessible by procedure 3.3.1 or 3.3.2
of this appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.3.1 The sample for that pipe or pipe segment shall only be taken at one end and a written notation documented in the
sampling and analysis records as to why only one sample was taken. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.3.2 Select another pipe segment using the random selection procedure in 3.4.2 of this appendix, or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.3.3.3 In the event that there is no other pipe or pipeline in the population to be sampled and both ends of a pipe have
porous surfaces at all possible sample collection sites, then the pipe segment or pipe shall be assumed to contain
greater than 50 but less than 500 ppm PCBs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4 Selection of a pipe segment from a length of pipe or population (group) of pipe segments. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.1 For purposes of wipe sampling pipe segments, the segments shall not exceed 12.1 meters (40 feet) in length. In
the event that a segment is longer than 12.1 meters in length, the segment shall be cut so that all resulting segments
are 12.1 meters or less in length. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.2 Pipe segments removed from the ground for disposal shall be sampled at each end. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.2.1 When a length of pipe having seven or fewer segments is removed for purposes of disposal, samples shall be taken
at each end of each segment removed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.2.2 When a length of pipe having multiple contiguous segments less than 3 miles in total length is removed for purposes
of disposal, samples shall be taken at each end of the first and last segments removed and each end of five randomly chosen
segments in between. A total of seven segments shall be sampled. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.2.3 When a length of pipe having multiple contiguous segments more than 3 miles in total length is removed for purposes
of disposal, samples shall be taken at each end of the first segment and each end of each segment that is one-half mile
distant from the segment previously sampled. A minimum of seven segments shall be sampled. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.3 Sampling of Pipe to Be Abandoned in Place 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.3.1 Procedures in 761.60(b)(5)(iii)(B) shall be followed first to assure the absence of free flowing liquids.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.3.2 Both ends of all pipe to be abandoned in place are to be sampled, samples shall be taken at each end of each pipe.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.3.3 For abandonment of pipe exceeding 50 miles but less than 100 miles in length, an additional sample at the midpoint
shall be taken. Sampling the midpoint sample may be taken by removing all covering soil and cutting the pipe to gain
access to the sampling location in lieu of removing a segment of pipe. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.4.3.4 For abandonment of pipe exceeding 100 miles in length, both ends and a point every 50 miles from the downstream
(of the direction of the former gas flow) shall be sampled. Internal samples may be collected by removing any covering
soil and cutting the pipe to gain access to the sampling location in lieu of removing segments of pipe. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 4.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Chemical Analysis
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1 Sample Extraction and Chemical Analysis Procedures. Section 761.60(g) provides guidance on chemical analysis
procedures. Extraction and cleanup of the extract shall be in accordance with applicable extraction and cleanup
procedures for the analysis of PCB soil samples in SW&hyph;846, ``Test Methods for Evaluating Solid Waste,'' which
is available from either the National Technical Information Service (NTIS, U.S. Department of Commerce, 5285 Port
Royal Rd, Springfield, VA 22161, telephone: (703) 487&hyph;4650) or the U.S. Government Printing Office (U.S. GPO,
710 No. Capitol St., NW., Washington, DC 20401, telephone: (202) 783&hyph;3238). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2 Reporting the PCB Concentrations in Samples. All sample concentrations shall be reported on the basis of micrograms
of PCBs per 100 square centimeter of surface sampled. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Determining the Regulatory Status of Sampled Pipe
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.1 For purposes of disposal: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.1.1 The analytical results of both samples from each segment sampled shall be averaged to determine the level of
contamination in that segment. This average will be referred to as an averaged sample result. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.1.2 If the averaged sample result, from any segment sampled from a removal population is greater than 10 micrograms
PCB/100 square centimeters then that segment is considered contaminated with PCBs. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.1.3 From a multiple contiguous segment removal project, all unsampled segments in the removal project are presumed
contaminated with PCBs at the same PCB concentration as was found in the segment having the highest averaged sample
PCB concentration. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2 For purposes of abandonment: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.1 The entire pipe to be abandoned shall be presumed to have the same concentration as the highest measured average
sample result. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=2 -->
 APPENDIX II _ Sampling to Verify Completion of Self-Implementing Disposal of PCB Remediation Waste. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=2 -->
 1.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Application and Scope
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.0 The following is required when sampling to verify completion of the cleanup for self-implementing disposal of
PCB remediation waste. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Minimum Number of Samples
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.0 Regardless of the amount of each type of PCB remediation waste present at a PCB remediation site, a minimum of samples
shall be taken. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.1 For each type of PCB remediation waste present at the remediation site and at each separate site within a facility,
a minimum of three samples shall be taken. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.2 For each sample, the PCB concentration shall be measured, recorded and kept on file. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.3 This is an example of a minimum number of samples calculation at a PCB remediation waste location. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
There are three distinct, sites at the location: a loading dock, a transformer storage lot, and a disposal pit. The
minimum number of samples appears after each type of waste for each site. The PCB remediation wastes present at the
loading dock are concrete (3), and clay soil (3). The PCB remediation wastes present at the transformer storage lot
are oily soil (3), clay soil (3), and gravel (3). The PCB remediation wastes present at the disposal pit are sandy soil
(3), clay soil (3), oily soil (3), industrial sludge (3), sludge aqueous decantate (3) and gravel (3). For purposes
of the self-implementing cleanup and disposal of these PCB remediation wastes, the minimum total number of samples
needed to verify cleanup at this entire site as described is procedure 3.0 of this appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 3.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Materials to be Sampled at a Site
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.0 Samples shall be collected of bulk materials and on the surface of all areas which contacted PCBs or PCB materials
and which were removed for purposes of disposal during the remediation. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 4.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Determination of Sample Collection Locations 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.0 Once remediation is assumed to be complete, the following procedure shall be used. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1 Sample collection locations shall be based on a hexagonal grid system similar to the one employed in the document
``Field Manual for Grid Sampling of PCB Spill Sites to Verify Cleanup'' (EPA-560/5&hyph;86&hyph;017), except that
the interval between adjacent sampling points shall be 1 meter. Copies of the grid sampling manual may be obtained
from the TSCA Hotline by calling (202) 554&hyph;1404. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2 There is no upper limit to the number of samples required or allowed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3 In the event that a site is sufficiently small or oddly configured that a hexagonal grid with the grid interval of
one meter will not place the minimum of three sampling points in the site, then sampling coordinates shall be selected
based on the following random sampling scheme. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.1 There shall be no sample compositing for this kind of small site and oddly configured sites. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2 Designate the length and width of the area as the two axes of a two-dimensional Cartesian coordinate grid system.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3 The grid system is to be oriented so that its origin is nearest to the lower left corner of the area to be sampled.
When this Cartesian system is oriented this way, the entire area falls into the first (upper right or positive on both
axes) quadrant of the grid. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4 Measure the length of each axis (length and width) in centimeters (or inches). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.5 Select an eligible set of two coordinates in centimeters (or inches) from a random number table or random number
generator for each of the minimum of three samples to be taken. Eligible means that the point defined by the selected
coordinates falls in the area cleaned up. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.6 A third coordinate is not necessary. Samples shall be taken on the surface of the location left after cleanup
has been completed. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 5.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Collection of Samples
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.0 Sample collection procedures differ for surfaces and bulk PCB remediation wastes. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.1 Flat non-porous surfaces shall be wipe sampled at the selected grid point. Individual surface samples shall be
no smaller than 100 square centimeters. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2 Sampling of Bulk PCB Remediation Wastes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.1 At each sampling grid point, core samples shall be collected from at least one and no more than four different
locations surrounding each grid point. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2 Each core sample around the grid point shall be no closer than 10 centimeters (4 inches) and no farther than forty
centimeters (16 inches) from the grid point. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.1 If more than one core sample is taken at a grid point, all of these samples shall be composited (see procedure
6.0 of this appendix) and mixed thoroughly into a single sample representing the grid point. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.2 Core sampling for bulk PCB remediation waste having particle size diameter of less than or equal to one centimeter.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.2.1 Each sample shall be collected using a 2.5 centimeter (1 inch) or 2 centimeter diameter core sampler. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.2.2 Each core sample shall be taken to a depth of 2.5 centimeters below the surface 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.3 Core sampling for bulk PCB remediation waste having particle size diameter of greater than one centimeter.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.3.1 Each core sample shall be taken by a core having a diameter no less than two and a half times the diameter of
the average particle in the material. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.2.2.3.2 The depth of the core sample shall be two and a half times the estimated average diameter of the particles
in the waste. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.3 Sampling of Porous Surfaces 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
5.3.1 Porous surfaces such as asphalt, wood, and concrete, shall be core sampled as for bulk PCB remediation waste
having a particle size diameter of less than one centimeter (see procedure 5.2.2.2 of this appendix). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 6.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Compositing Samples
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.1 When compositing, all individual samples added to compose a composite sample shall be the same weight. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.2 All chemical analyses for PCBs in composite samples shall be by means of a gas chromatography with electron capture
detector (GC/EC) method such as EPA SW&hyph;846 Method 8080. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.3 Compositing bulk PCB remediation waste samples from more than one grid point. Bulk PCB remediation waste samples
from one grid may be composited so long as the PCB concentration of interest (the clean/not clean level) is divided
by the number of samples in the composite. The resulting quotient shall be called the ``composite action level.''
The composite action level eliminates the possibility that any one sample in the composite is above the PCB concentration
of interest. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.3.1 If the concentration from the analysis of the composite exceeds the ``composite action level,'' then it shall
be assumed that at least one sample in the composite exceeds the PCB concentration of interest. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.3.1.1 For example, for bulk PCB remediation waste samples, if the concentration of interest is 50 ppm and then ten
samples are composited and analyzed, then the ``composite action level'' is 5 ppm. If the chemical analysis results
indicates less than 5 ppm, there are no samples having a concentration greater than 50 ppm (the PCB concentration of
interest). If the chemical analysis is 5 ppm or greater then there may be at least one sample in the composite having
a concentration exceeding the concentration of interest and further sampling and or compositing is necessary to
demonstrate that no sample exceeds the concentration of interest. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.3.2 If the concentration from the analysis of the composite is less than the ``composite action level,'' then it
shall be assumed that none of the individual samples in the composite exceeds the PCB concentration of interest. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.4 Compositing wipe samples from non-porous samples from more than one grid point. When accounting for dilution
from compositing wipe samples, it is not necessary to use samples wiped from the same total surface area so long as the
``composite action level'' (see procedure 6.1 of this appendix) assumes the smallest surface area from any of the
wipe samples composited. This difference from bulk remediation waste sample compositing is the result of the PCB
amount reported being a weight rather than a concentration. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
6.4.1 For example, if the PCB concentration of interest is 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=6 f=2 -->
;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
10 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=6 f=1 -->
m
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
g/100 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 and the sample gauze from three wipe samples each of an area of 200 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 are composited with one sample of 100 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
. If the report for this composite showed greater than 10 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=6 f=1 -->
m
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
g, it shall be assumed that at least one of the wipe samples exceeded the PCB concentration of interest because the smallest
area in the samples composited was 100 cm
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=5 f=1 -->
2
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
7.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Reporting the PCB Concentrations in Samples 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
All sample concentrations are to be reported on the basis of micrograms of PCBs per gram of dry bulk PCB remediation
waste (and porous surfaces) and on a micrograms of PCBs per 100 square centimeter basis for non-porous surfaces. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 8.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Decisions Based on Sample Concentration Resulting from this Sampling Scheme 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
8.1 If, for the sampled type of waste at a designated site, any grid point sample PCB concentration exceeds the concentration
of interest or the PCB concentration of a composite sample exceeds the composite action level, then the type of waste
at the site has not been successfully cleaned up and, for purposes of self-implementing disposal, further cleanup
is required. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
8.2 In the event that further cleanup is required in paragraph 8.0 of this appendix, all of the type of waste at a particular
site at a facility (or any portion of the site) may be recleaned. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
8.3 Following the recleaning, the procedure to verify the completeness of the cleanup shall be reinitiated (starting
at paragraph 4.0 of this appendix) to determine whether the requirements have been met. This ``reverification''
shall include that the verification sampling grid be reoriented and all of the type of waste at a particular site at
the facility shall be resampled as required in paragraph 4.0&hyph;7.0 above. Cleaning a portion of the site and sampling
only the portion which was recleaned does not comply with these self-implementing PCB remediation waste cleanup
requirements. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
For example, assume that random samples were collected to verify a site remediation under 761.61(a) and one of the
samples of seven taken in a grid sampling plot had a concentration above the PCB concentration of concern. The site
represented by the seven grid samples may be recleaned only in the area surrounding that one sample. However, following
recleaning, the entire site must be resampled using a new set of seven grid samples, collected from a reoriented grid,
to verify that the cleanup resulted in no PCBs in any of the seven grid samples above the PCB concentration of concern.
This sampling procedure does not allow only resampling the areas which were recleaned. Nor does this sampling procedure
allow using the arithmetic mean or any other statistical evaluation of the results from several samples to arrive
at an overall ``average'' site concentration. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=52 g=1 f=2 -->
APPENDIX III. _ Sampling Non-Liquid, Non-Metal Non-Remediation Waste Generated by Processing Materials Containing
Recyclable Metals 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=2 -->
1.0 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
Defining and Characterizing a Single Feed Source Population 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.1 A single feed source includes, but is not limited to automobiles, a mixture of a fixed ratio of automobiles plus
white goods, white goods, and wire cable from a single source such as a ship. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
1.2 Once a population of processed PCB non-remediation waste from a single feed source is characterized it is not necessary
to recharacterize PCB non-remediation waste from that feed source so long as there are no changes in the feed source
which are expected to change the PCB content in that feed source. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 2.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Accumulate the Population to Be Sampled 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.1 Accumulate all PCB non-remediation waste generated from a single source in one location in a container, a pile
or piles. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
2.2 When all PCB non-remediation waste from a single source cannot be processed in a day, all source PCB non-remediation
waste for one day of full-time, full-scale processing shall be accumulated in a discrete, container, several containers,
or identifiable pile (or piles). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Number of Samples and Size of Samples and Sub-Samples 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.1 To characterize a population of non-liquid PCB non-remediation waste accumulated in a pile or piles, it is necessary
to collect seven approximately 100 milliliter (just less than 0.5 cup or approximately 100 grams) subsamples. These
seven sub-samples shall be composited into one sample in a covered wide-mouth one liter (one quart) jar. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
3.2 Pieces of PCB non-remediation waste larger than half of the sub-sample size (approximately 50 milliliters, 50
grams, or 0.25 cup) shall be excluded from a sub-sample. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.0
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=3 -->
 Sample Site Selection and Sub-Sample/Sample Collection 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1 Selection of the Piles from which Sub-Samples Will Be Collected 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1.1 If the processed PCB non-remediation waste from a single source consists of more than one pile or container,
each pile or container shall be assigned an integer number and then seven random integer numbers shall be generated
to select piles (from which sub-samples shall be collected) from the population of all piles. It is possible that this
random selection procedure will result in selecting the same pile number more than once, even if seven or more piles
are present. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.1.2 If only one pile or container is present, all seven samples shall be taken from the same pile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2 Collecting Sub-Samples from Flattened Piles or Containers 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
If possible, spread the pile(s) out to a uniform thickness of approximately 1 foot (or 30 centimeters [cm]) into a rectangular
or a circular shape. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.1 For a circular shape flattened pile or cylindrical container: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.1.1 Use the procedures in the PCB Spill Cleanup manual (a triangular/hexagonal grid system) to select the seven
surface points for each composite sample for each flattened pile or container. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.1.2 Measure the depth of the pile at each sampling point in inches or centimeters. Randomly select a number of inches
or centimeters down from the surface using a random number generator. Then collect a 50 gram sample at the selected
depth. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.1.3 Composite the seven 50 gram samples collected from the seven sampling locations into a single sample for analysis.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.2 For a rectangular shape flattened pile or boxshaped container there are two options a random coordinate option
(procedure 4.2.2.1 of this appendix) and a grid option (procedure 4.2.2.2 of this appendix): 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.2.1 Designate the length, width, and depth of the flattened pile or container as three axes of a three dimensional
Cartesian coordinate grid system. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.2.1.1 Measure the length of each axis (length, width, and depth) in centimeters (or inches). Using a random number
generator, select an eligible set of three coordinates in centimeters (or inches) for each of seven sub-samples to
be taken. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.2.1.2 Collect each sub-sample at the location selected and composite the sub-samples into a single sample for
analysis. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.2.2.2 Use the grid sampling procedure in the Field Manual which is part of the ``Sampling Guidance for Scrap Metal
Shredders.'' Briefly described, this procedure divides the length and width of a flattened pile into three equal
segments, intersection of the length segments with the width segments results in a 3 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=6 f=1 -->
&times;
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=21 g=1 f=1 -->
 3 grid or nine cells. The length and width shall be chosen to be perpendicular. Samples shall be collected at the center
of each cell on the surface. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3 Collecting Sub-samples from Unflattened Piles 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
If the pile is too large to be spread on the site to a uniform thickness of 1 foot or 30 centimeters, or there are too many
piles to spread out in the working area, the following procedure can be used to sample the piles. This procedure assumes
that the shape of the piles is roughly conical; that is, having a circular base with PCB non-remediation waste stacked
up uniformly to a peak which is roughly a point centered above the center of the circular base. For each sub-sample,
three sample site coordinates will be selected. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.1 Setting Up the Sample Site Selection System 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.1.1 Use a rod, dowel, stake, or broom handle as a marker. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.1.1.1 Nail or otherwise fasten to the top of the marker a piece of string or cord of sufficient length and strength
to reach from the top of the marker to the farthest peripheral edge of the pile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.1.1.2 Pound or push the marker into the top center (apex) of the pile downward toward the center of the base at least
30 centimeters or one foot until the marker is rigidly standing on its own, even when the cord is pulled tight to the bottom
of the pile. The marker shall protrude from the top of the pile sufficiently to allow easy movement around the pile with
the tightened string. A side view of a pile with a marker and string is illustrated below. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2 Select the first coordinate as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.1 Use a random number to generate a number between 0 and 360. The number generated is the number of degrees from
magnetic north. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.2 In a pile containing a lot of ferrous metal, the ferrous metal may have sufficient magnetism to deflect the
compass needle. Confirm the magnetic north direction at a location distant from a pile of metal before assuming that
the compass is not effected by local magnetism. In the event that the compass needle is deflected by the material to
be sampled, this sampling procedure shall not be used and the material to be sampled shall then be flattened. Once the
material is flattened, the sampling procedures in procedure 4.2 of this Appendix shall be used. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3 Use a magnetic compass to determine this direction on the pile as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3.1 Pull the cord to the bottom of the pile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3.2 Orient the compass so that the needle is pointing to magnetic north (At this point it may be helpful to sketch
a picture of the top view of the pile oriented to magnetic north and draw a line from the center of the pile outward in the
direction of the selected coordinate. (This drawing can be used to locate the approximate coordinate in the next step
and may be used to document the sampling location.). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3.3 With the cord slightly slack, hold the cord and walk around the outside edge of the pile to be sampled until
the approximate coordinate is reached. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3.4 Tighten the cord and place the compass directly under the tightened cord at the bottom edge of the pile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.3.5 Move around the outside of the pile with the cord laying over the center of the compass and with the needle
pointing to magnetic north and stop when the cord lies over the selected coordinate direction on the compass. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.4 Mark this first coordinate by tying the cord to a peg or placing it under a heavy weight. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.2.5 An illustration of the orientation of a magnetic compass and the cord with respect to a pile appears below 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3 Select the second coordinate as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3.1 Once the first coordinate has been fixed, along the first coordinate (the cord), measure the distance in centimeters
(or inches) from the bottom edge of the pile to the point where the marker meets the top of the pile. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3.2 Select a random number between 0 and the total number of centimeters (inches) measured in paragraph 4.3.3.1
of this appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3.3 Proceed up the cord, from the bottom of the pile to the top, the selected number of centimeters (inches). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.3.4 Pound or push a marker rod, dowel or broom handle down into the pile until the marker is secure to mark the second
coordinate point. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4 Select the third (final) coordinate as follows: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4.1 Measure or estimate the vertical distance in centimeters (or inches) from the surface of the pile at the second
coordinate marker to the bottom of the pile or ground level. This distance will be referred to as ``vertical distance.''

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4.2 Select a random number between 0 and the total number of centimeters (inches) of vertical distance. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4.3 Dig a hole straight down into the pile the selected number of centimeters (inches) from the surface of the pile.
The hole shall be of sufficient distance from the second coordinate marker so as to allow the marker to remain in place.

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4.4 Slowly dig over to expose the second coordinate marker and collect the sub-sample on any side of this marker
at the depth selected in paragraph 4.3.4.2 of this appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
4.3.4.5 In the event that the measurement or estimate of the distance to the bottom of the pile or the ground level was
too large and the selected depth is below the bottom of the pile, reselect a random number as indicated in paragraph
4.3.4.2 of this appendix using the vertical distance determined by digging as indicated in paragraph 4.3.4.3 of this
appendix. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

